{"title_page": "2019 NBA Finals", "text_new": "{{short description|The 2019 edition of the NBA Finals between Golden State and Toronto}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{NBA Finals summary\n| image = 2019 NBA Finals logo.png\n| league = NBA\n| year = 2019\n| champion = [[2018\u201319 Toronto Raptors season|Toronto Raptors]]\n| champion_coach = [[Nick Nurse]]\n| champion_games = 4\n| runnerup = [[2018\u201319 Golden State Warriors season|Golden State Warriors]]\n| runnerup_coach = [[Steve Kerr]]\n| runnerup_games = 2\n| date = May 30 \u2013 June 13\n| MVP = [[Kawhi Leonard]]<br />(Toronto Raptors)\n| television = '''Canada''':<br />English: [[Sportsnet]]/[[Citytv]] (Games 1, 3, and 5),<br />[[The Sports Network|TSN]]/[[CTV 2]] (Games 2 and 4)<br />TSN/[[CTV Television Network|CTV]] (Game 6)<br />French: [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]]<br />'''United States''':<br />English: [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]<br />Spanish: [[ESPN Deportes]]\n| announcers = '''Canada''':{{unbulleted list|[[Matt Devlin (sportscaster)|Matt Devlin]] (play-by-play)|[[Leo Rautins]] (Sportsnet analyst)|[[Jack Armstrong (basketball)|Jack Armstrong]] (TSN analyst)|Alexandre Tourigny (RDS play-by-play)|Will Archambault (RDS analyst)}}'''United States''':{{unbulleted list|[[Mike Breen]] (ABC play-by-play)|[[Jeff Van Gundy]]/[[Mark Jackson]] (ABC analysts)|[[Doris Burke]] (ABC sideline reporter)|[[\u00c1lvaro Mart\u00edn (sports announcer)|\u00c1lvaro Mart\u00edn]] (ESPN Deportes play-by-play)|Carlos Morales (ESPN Deportes analyst)}}\n| HOFers =\n| radio_network = [[NBA on ESPN Radio|ESPN Radio]] ([[English language|English]] ([[United States]]))<br />[[KGMZ-FM|Golden State Warriors Radio Network]] ([[Golden State Warriors|Golden State]])<br />[[CJCL|Sportsnet 590 The FAN]] ([[Toronto Raptors|Toronto]])<br />[[CHUM (AM)|TSN Radio 1050]] ([[Toronto Raptors|Toronto]])\n| radio_announcers = [[Marc Kestecher]] and [[Hubie Brown]] ([[NBA on ESPN Radio|ESPN Radio]])<br />[[Tim Roye]], [[Jim Barnett (basketball)|Jim Barnett]] and [[Tom Tolbert]] ([[Golden State Warriors|Golden State]])<br />[[Eric Smith (sportscaster)|Eric Smith]] and [[Paul Jones (sportscaster)|Paul Jones]] and Sherman Hamilton  ([[Toronto Raptors|Toronto]])\n| referees_1 = James Capers, Jason Phillips, John Goble \n| referees_2 = Scott Foster, [[Tony Brothers]], Ed Malloy\n| referees_3 = Marc Davis, David Guthrie, Kane Fitzgerald\n| referees_4 = Mike Callahan, [[Zach Zarba]], Eric Lewis\n| referees_5 = James Capers, Jason Phillips, Ed Malloy\n| referees_6 = Marc Davis, David Guthrie, John Goble\n| ECF result = [[2018\u201319 Toronto Raptors season|Raptors]] defeated [[2018\u201319 Milwaukee Bucks season|Bucks]], 4\u20132 \n| WCF result = [[2018\u201319 Golden State Warriors season|Warriors]] defeated [[2018\u201319 Portland Trail Blazers season|Trail Blazers]], 4\u20130\n}}\nThe '''2019 NBA Finals''' was the [[NBA Finals|championship series]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA)'s [[2018\u201319 NBA season|2018\u201319 season]] and conclusion of the [[2019 NBA playoffs|season's playoffs]]. In the [[best-of-seven playoff]] series held from May 30 through June 13, 2019, the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] champion [[2018\u201319 Toronto Raptors season|Toronto Raptors]] defeated the [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] champion [[2018\u201319 Golden State Warriors season|Golden State Warriors]], {{tooltip|4\u20132|four games to two}}, earning the franchise its first [[NBA championship]] as well as the first win by a team based outside the United States. Acquired by the Raptors via a trade during the off-season, [[Kawhi Leonard]] was named the [[NBA Finals Most Valuable Player]] (MVP) for the second time in his career.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kawhi Leonard joins elite company in winning Finals MVP|url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/06/13/finals-mvps-more-one-team|website=NBA.com|date=June 13, 2019|access-date=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis was the first NBA Finals appearance for the Raptors, and the league's first finals with games played outside of the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=How long has it been since each team last made The Finals?|url=https://www.nba.com/longest-gap-between-finals-appearances?collection=news|website=NBA.com|date=May 26, 2019|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> [[Home-court advantage]] was awarded to Toronto, who finished the regular season with one more win (58\u201324) than Golden State (57\u201325). This was the first time in five consecutive NBA Finals appearances that the then-two-time defending NBA-champion Warriors did not have home-court advantage.<ref name=cacciola_05202019/> Also for the first time after the past four postseasons, the Warriors and the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] did not meet in the championship round.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schuhmann|first=John|title=Road Warriors: For first time in five Finals, Golden State opens title series on road|url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/05/29/road-warriors|website=NBA.com|date=May 29, 2019|access-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref> This was the first finals since [[2010 NBA Finals|2010]] not to include [[LeBron James]], who played in the past eight finals with the Cavaliers and the [[Miami Heat]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Paine|first=Neil|title=This Is The First NBA Finals In 9 Years Without LeBron. (A Lot Has Changed.)|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/this-is-the-first-nba-finals-in-9-years-without-lebron-a-lot-has-changed/|website=[[FiveThirtyEight]].com|date=May 29, 2019|access-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\n===Golden State Warriors===\n{{Main|2018\u201319 Golden State Warriors season}}\nDuring the off-season, Golden State acquired [[DeMarcus Cousins]], who was recovering from a [[Achilles tendon rupture|ruptured left Achilles]]. He gave the Warriors a true, top-flight [[center (basketball)|center]] for the first time under head coach [[Steve Kerr]].<ref name=ap_01182019>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071352|title=Warriors beat Clippers 112-94; Boogie fouls out of debut|work=ESPN.com|date=January 18, 2019|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=May 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502222127/http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071352|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=gorcey_04132019>{{cite news|last=Gorcey|first=Ryan|title=Warriors: Death Lineup makes early appearance against Clippers, turns tide|date=April 13, 2019|newspaper=San Francisco Examiner|url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/sports/warriors-death-lineup-makes-early-appearance-against-clippers-turns-tide/|accessdate=May 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508081048/https://www.sfexaminer.com/sports/warriors-death-lineup-makes-early-appearance-against-clippers-turns-tide/|archive-date=May 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During an overtime loss to the [[2018\u201319 Los Angeles Clippers season|Los Angeles Clippers]] in November 2018, [[Draymond Green]] cursed out teammate [[Kevin Durant]] over his upcoming [[Free agent|free agency]] status after the season, and he was suspended for the much-publicized blowup.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shelburne|first=Ramona|title=How Draymond Green found his zen|date=June 4, 2019|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26891462/how-draymond-green-found-zen|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Murdock|first=Logan|title=Draymond Green Again Proves He's the Ultimate Winner in Closeout Win|url=https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/sports/csn/warriors/Draymond_Green_again_proves_he_s_the_ultimate_winner_in_closeout_win_BAY.html|publisher=[[KNTV]]|website=NBCBayArea.com|date=May 21, 2019|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=bontemps_05262019>{{cite news|last=Bontemps|first=Tim|title=What we know and don't know about this Warriors-Raptors Finals|url=http://global.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26814726/what-know-know-warriors-raptors-finals|website=ESPN.com|date=May 26, 2019|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, Cousins returned, and the Warriors became the first team in 42 years with a starting lineup of five [[NBA All-Star]]s from the previous season.<ref name=ap_01182019/> The team finished the regular season with a 57\u201325 record, winning the [[Pacific Division (NBA)|Pacific Division]] and securing the 1st seed in the Western Conference.<ref>{{cite news|last=Valenzuela|first=Sarah|title=Raptors vs. Warriors: Everything you need to know about the 2019 NBA Finals|date=May 29, 2019|newspaper=New York Daily News|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/basketball/ny-sports-nba-finals-2019-guide-20190529-lbefmopquffhlp2mw6i7rtypoe-story.html|accessdate=June 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the playoffs, Golden State defeated the Clippers in six games in the first round, despite blowing leads at home in Games 2 and 5.<ref name=bontemps_05262019/> Cousins tore his left [[quadriceps femoris muscle|quadriceps]] in Game 2, and was initially thought to be out for the remainder of the postseason.<ref>{{cite news|title=Warriors-Rockets II: Everything to know for the must-see sequel|date=April 27, 2019|website=ESPN.com|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26575159/warriors-rockets-ii-everything-know-playoffs-see-sequel|accessdate=May 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502105129/http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26575159/warriors-rockets-ii-everything-know-playoffs-see-sequel|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> With an increased urgency and in a sign of respect towards their opponent, Kerr opened the following round against the [[2018\u201319 Houston Rockets season|Houston Rockets]] by moving [[Andre Iguodala]] from the [[Substitution (sport)|bench]] and [[starting lineup|starting]] the [[Death Lineup|Hamptons Five]] for the first time in the season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|title=Warriors Start Hamptons Five, Showing Urgency in Win Over Rockets|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/28/sports/warriors-rockets-nba-playoffs.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 28, 2019|access-date=May 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508081048/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/28/sports/warriors-rockets-nba-playoffs.html|archive-date=May 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Helin|first=Kurt|title=After Game 1, Steve Kerr says 'it's a series where we can play more people'|url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2019/05/15/after-game-1-steve-kerr-says-its-a-series-where-we-can-play-more-people/|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=May 15, 2019|access-date=May 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516195401/https://nba.nbcsports.com/2019/05/15/after-game-1-steve-kerr-says-its-a-series-where-we-can-play-more-people/|archive-date=May 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> With the [[Splash Brothers]], Warriors guards [[Stephen Curry]] and [[Klay Thompson]], struggling with their shooting, Durant had been the team's best player in the playoffs, averaging a team-leading 35.4 points entering Game 5.<ref name=turbow_05092019>{{cite news|last=Turbow|first=Jason|title=Kevin Durant Pulled From Game 5 Against Rockets With Leg Injury|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/09/sports/warriors-rockets-kevin-durant-calf-achilles.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 9, 2019|access-date=May 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518175315/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/09/sports/warriors-rockets-kevin-durant-calf-achilles.html|archive-date=May 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Durant left the game late in the third quarter after suffering a strained right calf;<ref name=turbow_05092019/><ref name=medina_05102019/> he was later ruled out indefinitely. Led by Curry and Thompson, Golden State pulled out Game 5 without Durant, and won the series in six games.<ref name=medina_05102019>{{cite news|last=Medina|first=Mark|title=Warriors know Game 6 will require an extra helping of Curry|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/05/10/steph-curry-on-playing-without-kevin-durant-i-have-to-play-well-and-be-aggressive/|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|date=May 10, 2019|access-date=May 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510235912/https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/05/10/steph-curry-on-playing-without-kevin-durant-i-have-to-play-well-and-be-aggressive/|archive-date=May 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Letourneau|first=Connor|title=Stephen Curry\u2019s late heroics lift the Warriors to series-clinching Game 6 win|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/warriors/article/Stephen-Curry-s-late-heroics-lift-the-Warriors-13837370.php|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=May 10, 2019|access-date=May 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515215503/https://www.sfchronicle.com/warriors/article/Stephen-Curry-s-late-heroics-lift-the-Warriors-13837370.php|archive-date=May 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the Western Conference finals, Golden State swept the [[2018\u201319 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]] 4\u20130, with three of the wins including comebacks of 15 points or more.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mahoney|first=Rob|title=En Route to Fifth Straight Finals, Warriors Show They\u2019re the Greatest Comeback Team in NBA History|date=May 21, 2019|work=SI.com|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2019/05/21/warriors-trail-blazers-finals-steph-curry-draymond-green-game-4-sweep|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref><ref name=friedell_05202019/> After starting nine consecutive games,<ref name=cacciola_05202019/> Iguodala missed the deciding Game 4 with a sore left calf injury from Game 3.<ref name=friedell_05202019>{{cite news|last=Friedell|first=Nick|title=Warriors first to 5 Finals in row since 1966 Celtics|url=http://global.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26791178/warriors-first-5-finals-row-1966-celtics|website=ESPN.com|date=May 20, 2019|access-date=May 21, 2019}}</ref> Curry averaged a series career-high 36.5 points, the highest average by a player in a four-game sweep in NBA history.<ref>{{cite news|last=Windhorst|first=Brian|title=Peak Stephen Curry was unleashed in the Western Conference finals|url=http://global.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26791489/peak-stephen-curry-was-unleashed-western-conference-finals|website=ESPN.com|date=May 21, 2019|access-date=May 22, 2019}}</ref> This was Golden State's fifth consecutive trip to the NBA Finals. They were the second team in NBA history to achieve this feat, joining the [[Boston Celtics]], who played in ten straight Finals (1957\u20131966).{{efn|The Celtics advanced 10 straight times, winning nine, including eight consecutive.<ref name=cacciola_05202019>{{cite news|last=Cacciola|first=Scott|title=Warriors Sweep Blazers to Reach Their 5th Straight N.B.A. Finals|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/20/sports/warriors-nba-finals.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 20, 2019|access-date=May 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521084901/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/20/sports/warriors-nba-finals.html|archive-date=May 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\n===Toronto Raptors===\n{{Main|2018\u201319 Toronto Raptors season}}\n[[File:2019 nba finals game 2.jpg|thumb|Game 2 at Toronto, which Golden State won]]\nDuring the off-season, the Raptors fired coach [[Dwane Casey]], who was named the 2018 [[NBA Coach of the Year]] weeks later, and replaced him with assistant coach [[Nick Nurse]]. They also traded [[DeMar DeRozan]] and [[Jakob P\u00f6ltl]] to the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in exchange for [[Kawhi Leonard]] and [[Danny Green (basketball)|Danny Green]].<ref name=bontemps_05262019/> The move stunned the All-Star DeRozan, who had become a fan favorite in his nine seasons in Toronto.<ref name=wong_05262019>{{cite news|last=Wong|first=Alex|title=With Kawhi Leonard, the Raptors Find Success That Endures|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/26/sports/toronto-raptors-kawhi-leonard-finals.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 26, 2019|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=stein_05292019>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|title=Kawhi Leonard Proves He Is Worth Risking It All|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/29/sports/kawhi-leonard-raptors-finals.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 29, 2019|access-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref> It was a risky move for the Raptors and their president, [[Masai Ujiri]], as Leonard was one year away from becoming a [[free agent]],<ref name=wong_05262019/> and he wanted to leave the Spurs after playing in just nine games in [[2017\u201318 San Antonio Spurs season|2017\u201318]] due to [[tendinopathy]] in his left [[Quadriceps femoris muscle|quadriceps]].<ref name=bontemps_05262019/><ref name=stein_05292019/> However, the 2014 [[NBA Finals MVP]] made it through the season healthy while being systematically rested for 22 games.<ref name=bontemps_05262019/><ref name=stein_05292019/> During the season, Toronto also traded a package that included [[Jonas Valan\u010di\u016bnas]] to the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] in exchange for [[Marc Gasol]].<ref name=bontemps_05262019/>\n\nThe Raptors lost Game 1 of the first round to the [[2018\u201319 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]], but then they won the next four games in a row and won the series in five games. After trailing 2\u20131 against the [[2018\u201319 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]] in the Eastern Conference Semifinals,<ref>{{cite news|last=Gonzalez|first=John|title=The Raptors Were Trying to Tell Us They Were Great, We Just Weren\u2019t Listening|date=June 9, 2019|work=The Ringer|url=https://www.theringer.com/nba/2019/6/9/18658830/toronto-raptors-finals-warriors-odds-expectations|accessdate=June 10, 2019}}</ref> they defeated them in seven games, with Leonard hitting the game-winner at the buzzer as the ball bounced four times on the rim before falling in, the first buzzer beater in a Game 7 in the NBA playoffs.<ref name=stein_05292019/> Toronto advanced to the Eastern Conference Finals to face the [[2018\u201319 Milwaukee Bucks season|Milwaukee Bucks]]. Despite trailing 2\u20130, the Raptors won the next four games to advance to the Finals in six games,<ref name=wong_05262019/> as Leonard outplayed the Bucks' [[Giannis Antetokounmpo]], who won league MVP that season.<ref name=\"stein_05292019\" /> This was their first trip to the NBA Finals in franchise history,<ref>{{cite news|last=Stevenson|first=Jane|title=Raptors fans gather at Jurassic Park 'to be part of history'|url=https://torontosun.com/news/local-news/raptors-fans-gather-at-jurassic-park-to-be-part-of-history|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=May 25, 2019|access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> breaking a <!-- *** 25 is correct (2018-1994+1) *** -->25-year<!-- *** 25 is correct (2018-1994+1) *** --> [[Drought (sport)|drought]] for teams from Toronto appearing in the championship round of any of the four [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|major North American professional sports leagues]] since [[Major League Baseball]]'s [[Toronto Blue Jays]] won the [[1993 World Series]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Zillgitt|first=Jeff|title=Toronto ready to take center stage with Raptors in NBA Finals|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/playoffs/2019/05/28/toronto-takes-center-stage-raptors-nba-finals/1252425001/|publisher=[[Gannett]]|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=May 29, 2019|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Road to the Finals===\n{{Main|2019 NBA playoffs}}\n{| style=\"width:100%; font-size:90%\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=top\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:45%;\"|[[2018\u201319 Toronto Raptors season|Toronto Raptors]] ([[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] champion) !! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:45%;\"|[[2018\u201319 Golden State Warriors season|Golden State Warriors]] ([[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] champion)\n|-\n|align=right|\n{{2018\u201319 NBA East standings|team=TOR}} 2nd seed in the East, 2nd best league record\n!colspan=2|[[2018\u201319 NBA season|Regular season]]\n|{{2018\u201319 NBA West standings|team=GSW}} 1st seed in the West, 3rd best league record\n|-\n|align=right|Defeated the 7th seeded [[2018\u201319 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]], [[2019 NBA playoffs|4\u20131]]\n!colspan=2|First round\n|align=left|Defeated the 8th seeded [[2018\u201319 Los Angeles Clippers season|Los Angeles Clippers]], [[2019 NBA playoffs|4\u20132]]\n|-\n|align=right|Defeated the 3rd seeded [[2018\u201319 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]], [[2019 NBA playoffs|4\u20133]]\n!colspan=2|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|Defeated the 4th seeded [[2018\u201319 Houston Rockets season|Houston Rockets]], [[2019 NBA playoffs|4\u20132]]\n|-\n|align=right|Defeated the 1st seeded [[2018\u201319 Milwaukee Bucks season|Milwaukee Bucks]], [[2019 NBA playoffs|4\u20132]]\n!colspan=2|Conference Finals\n|align=left|Defeated the 3rd seeded [[2018\u201319 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]], [[2019 NBA playoffs|4\u20130]]\n|}\n\n===Regular season series===\nThe Raptors won the regular season series 2\u20130.\n{{basketballbox\n| bg=#fff\n| date = November 29, 2018\n| report = {{NBA Recap|2018|1129|id=GSWTOR#}}\n| team1 = [[Golden State Warriors]] | score1 = 128\n| team2 = '''[[Toronto Raptors]]''' | score2 = '''131''' |overtime=OT\n| place = [[Scotiabank Arena]], [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n}}\n{{basketballbox\n| date = December 12, 2018\n| report = {{NBA Recap|2018|1212|id=TORGSW#}}\n| team1 = '''Toronto Raptors''' | score1 = '''113'''\n| team2 = Golden State Warriors | score2 = 93\n| place = [[Oakland Arena|Oracle Arena]], [[Oakland, California]]\n}}\n\n==Series summary==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Game\n! scope=\"col\"|Date\n! scope=\"col\"|Away Team\n! scope=\"col\"|Result\n! scope=\"col\"|Home Team\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Game 1\n| Thursday, May 30 || Golden State Warriors || 109\u2013118 (0\u20131) || '''Toronto Raptors'''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Game 2\n| Sunday, June 2 || '''Golden State Warriors'''|| 109\u2013104 (1\u20131) || Toronto Raptors\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Game 3\n| Wednesday, June 5 || '''Toronto Raptors''' || 123\u2013109 (2\u20131)  || Golden State Warriors\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Game 4\n| Friday, June 7 || '''Toronto Raptors''' || 105\u201392 (3\u20131) || Golden State Warriors\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Game 5\n| Monday, June 10 || '''Golden State Warriors''' || 106\u2013105 (2\u20133) || Toronto Raptors\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Game 6\n| Thursday, June 13 || '''Toronto Raptors'''  || 114\u2013110 (4\u20132) || Golden State Warriors\n|-\n|}\n\n==Game summaries==\n{{Hatnote|Times listed are [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Daylight Time]] ([[UTC\u221204:00|UTC\u22124]]). For games in Oakland, the local time is also given ([[Pacific Time Zone|PDT]], [[UTC\u221207:00|UTC\u22127]]).}}\n\n===Game 1===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=May 30 |time=9:00 pm |place=[[Scotiabank Arena]], [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]] |TV=[[Sportsnet|SN]], [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]], [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1=[[Golden State Warriors]] |score1=109\n|team2='''[[Toronto Raptors]]''' |score2='''118'''\n|report=[http://www.nba.com/games/20190530/GSWTOR#/boxscore Box score]\n|Q1=21\u2013'''25''' |Q2=28\u2013'''34''' |Q3='''32'''\u201329 |Q4=28\u2013'''30'''\n|points1=[[Stephen Curry]] 34 |points2=[[Pascal Siakam]] 32\n|rebounds1=[[Draymond Green]] 10 |rebounds2=[[Kawhi Leonard|Leonard]], Siakam 8 each\n|assist1=Draymond Green 10 |assist2=[[Kyle Lowry]] 9\n|attendance=19,983\n|referee=James Capers, Jason Phillips, John Goble\n|series=Toronto leads series, 1\u20130\n}}\n[[Pascal Siakam]] scored a playoff career-high 32 points on 14-of-17 shooting to lead Toronto to a 118\u2013109 win over Golden State in the first ever NBA Finals game played outside the United States. The Raptors had a 10-point lead at the half. Siakam, the [[NBA Most Improved Player Award]] that season, shot 6-for-6 in the third quarter to keep the Warriors at bay. Toronto maintained a double-digit lead for most of the fourth quarter, countering every rally by Golden State.<ref name=ap=05302019>{{cite news|title=Raptors take NBA Finals opener, beat Warriors 118-109|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401134815|agency=Associated Press|website=ESPN.com|date=May 30, 2019|access-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeonard had 23 points, eight rebounds and five assists in his first NBA Finals game since he was named the Finals MVP in 2014. Gasol added 20 for the Raptors. Curry scored 34 and Thompson had 21 for Golden State, which had won Game 1 of the Finals in each of the last four years. Draymond Green had a [[triple-double]] with 10 points, 10 rebounds, and 10 assists. Cousins returned from a quadriceps injury to come off the bench in his first NBA Finals game.<ref name=ap=05302019/> After missing Game 4 of the Western Conference finals with a left calf injury, Iguodala left near the end of this game after limping and favoring his right leg.<ref>{{cite news|last=Medina|first=Mark|title=How bad is Andre Iguodala\u2019s latest injury and what does it mean for the Warriors?|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/05/30/andre-iguodala-with-a-new-injury-scare-in-warriors-game-1-loss-to-raptors/|newspaper=The Mercury News|date=May 30, 2019|access-date=June 2, 2019}}</ref> Durant, the MVP of the last two NBA Finals, traveled with the team to Toronto, but remained sidelined.<ref name=ap=05302019/>\n\n===Game 2===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 2 |time=8:00 pm |place=[[Scotiabank Arena]], [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]] |TV=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]/[[CTV 2]], [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]], [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1='''[[Golden State Warriors]]''' |score1='''109'''\n|team2=[[Toronto Raptors]] |score2=104\n|report=[http://www.nba.com/games/20190602/GSWTOR#/boxscore Box score]\n|Q1=26\u2013'''27''' |Q2=28\u2013'''32''' |Q3='''34'''\u201321 |Q4=21\u2013'''24'''\n|points1=[[Klay Thompson]] 25 |points2=[[Kawhi Leonard]] 34\n|rebounds1=[[DeMarcus Cousins|Cousins]], [[Draymond Green|Green]] 10 each |rebounds2=Kawhi Leonard 14\n|assist1=Draymond Green 9 |assist2=[[Pascal Siakam]] 4\n|attendance=20,014 \n|referee=Scott Foster, [[Tony Brothers]], Ed Malloy\n|series=Series tied, 1\u20131\n}}\n[[File:1 kawhi leonard 2019 nba finals (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|right|Leonard shooting a free throw in Game 2]]\nThompson scored a team-high 25 points, and the Warriors outscored the Raptors 18\u20130 to start the second half before holding off a late Toronto rally to win 109\u2013104.<ref name=stein_06022019>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|title=N.B.A. Finals: Warriors Tie Series With Raptors|date=June 2, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/02/sports/nba-finals-golden-state-warriors-toronto-raptors.html|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=ap_06022019>{{cite news|title=Warriors beat Raptors 109-104 to even NBA Finals|date=June 2, 2019|website=ESPN.com|agency=Associated Press|url=https://global.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401134816|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref> Thompson had 18 points in the first half to keep Golden State in the game. They trailed by 11 with almost two minutes left until halftime before cutting it to 59\u201354 at the half. The Warriors' 18 unanswered points to begin the second half were the most in NBA Finals history to start a half.<ref name=ap_06022019/> Thompson left the game in the fourth quarter with a left [[hamstring]] injury after landing awkwardly on a [[three-point field goal]] attempt.<ref name=stein_06022019/><ref name=ap_06022019/> Toronto scored 10 straight points to pull within two points at 106\u2013104, but Iguodala cemented the win with a three-pointer with 5.9 seconds remaining in the game.<ref name=ap_06022019/>\n\nCurry finished the game with 23 points after missing his first six shots of the game.<ref name=stein_06022019/> Cousins, who was moved into the starting lineup, had 11 points, 10 rebounds and six assists, and Green had 17 points, 10 rebounds and nine assists to fall one assist short of his fourth straight triple-double.<ref name=ap_06022019/> Warriors backup center [[Kevon Looney]] missed the second half with a chest contusion.<ref name=stein_06022019/><ref name=ap_06022019/> Leonard led the Raptors with 34 points and 14 rebounds, and [[Fred VanVleet]] added 17 points. Game 1 star Siakam scored just 12 points on 5-for-18 shooting. Toronto was held to 37.2 percent shooting for the game.<ref name=stein_06022019/>\n\n===Game 3===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 5 |time=9:00 pm {{small|(6:00 pm [[Pacific Time Zone|PDT]])}} |place=[[Oakland Arena|Oracle Arena]], [[Oakland, California]] |TV=[[Sportsnet|SN]]/[[Citytv]], [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]], [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1='''[[Toronto Raptors]]''' |score1='''123'''\n|team2=[[Golden State Warriors]] |score2=109\n|report=[http://www.nba.com/games/20190605/TORGSW#/boxscore Box score]\n|Q1='''36'''\u201329 |Q2='''24'''\u201323 |Q3='''36'''\u201331 |Q4='''27'''\u201326\n|points1=[[Kawhi Leonard]] 30|points2=[[Stephen Curry]] 47\n|rebounds1=[[Pascal Siakam]] 9|rebounds2=Stephen Curry 8\n|assist1=[[Kyle Lowry]] 9|assist2=Stephen Curry 7\n|attendance=19,596\n|referee=Marc Davis, David Guthrie, Kane Fitzgerald\n|series=Toronto leads series, 2\u20131\n}}\nLeonard scored 30 points and the Raptors shot 52.4% and made 17 three-pointers to win 123\u2013109 on the road over the short-handed Warriors.  Curry scored a playoff career-high 47 points, shooting 14 for 31 including 6 of 14 on 3-pointers,<ref name=ap_06052019/> while his teammates totaled 62 points on 36.7 percent shooting.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson II|first=Marcus|title=Thompson: The Warriors need some help because the Game 3 version of their lineup can\u2019t beat the Raptors|date=June 6, 2019|work=The Athletic|url=https://theathletic.com/1013873/2019/06/06/thompson-the-warriors-need-some-help-because-the-game-3-version-of-their-lineup-cant-beat-the-raptors/|url-access=subscription|accessdate=June 7, 2019}}</ref> Golden State played without injured starters Thompson and Durant, and backup big man Looney. Toronto's [[Kyle Lowry]] had 23 points and five 3-pointers, and [[Danny Green (basketball)|Danny Green]] added 18 points on 6 made 3s, as all five of their starters scored in double figures. VanVleet contributed 11 points off the bench.<ref name=ap_06052019>{{cite news|title=Raptors hit big shots, beat Warriors for 2-1 NBA Finals lead|date=June 5, 2019|website=ESPN.com|agency=Associtated Press|url=https://global.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401134817|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThompson practiced earlier in the day but did not warm up for the game. Kerr had said that the Warriors were not going to play him if there was risk of further damage.<ref name=ap_06052019/> Looney was out with a cartilage fracture near his right collarbone.<ref name=ap_06052019/><ref>{{cite news|title=Looney listed as questionable for Game 4|date=June 7, 2019|website=TSN.ca|url=https://www.tsn.ca/kevon-looney-listed-as-questionable-for-game-4-1.1318131|accessdate=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Game 4===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 7 |time=9:00 pm {{small|(6:00 pm [[Pacific Time Zone|PDT]])}}|place=[[Oracle Arena]], [[Oakland, California]] |TV=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]/[[CTV 2]], [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]], [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1='''[[Toronto Raptors]]''' |score1='''105'''\n|team2=[[Golden State Warriors]] |score2=92\n|report=[https://watch.nba.com/game/20190607/TORGSW Box score]\n|Q1=17\u2013'''23''' |Q2='''25'''\u201323 |Q3='''37'''\u201321 |Q4='''26'''\u201325\n|points1=[[Kawhi Leonard]] 36 |points2=[[Klay Thompson]] 28\n|rebounds1=Kawhi Leonard 12 |rebounds2=[[Draymond Green]] 9\n|assist1=[[Kyle Lowry]] 7 |assist2=Draymond Green 12\n|attendance=19,596\n|referee=Mike Callahan, [[Zach Zarba]], Eric Lewis\n|series=Toronto leads series, 3\u20131\n}}\n\nToronto took a 3\u20131 lead in the series after Leonard scored 36 points and had 12 rebounds in a 105\u201392 road win over Golden State.<ref name=ap_06072019>{{cite news|title=Leonard, Raptors move within victory of first championship|date=June 7, 2019|website=ESPN.com|agency=Associated Press|url=https://global.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401134818|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> The Raptors fell behind by 11 early in the contest,<ref name=ap_06072019/> and trailed 46\u201342 at halftime.<ref name=stein_06072019>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|title=The Raptors Won Game 4 and Are 1 Win From an N.B.A. Championship|date=June 7, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/07/sports/raptors-warriors-score.html|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> They outscored the Warriors 37\u201321 in the third quarter, when Leonard scored 17 of his points, and led by as many as 16 in the final quarter.<ref name=stein_06072019/> [[Serge Ibaka]] scored 20 points for Toronto, shooting 9 for 12 in 22 minutes off the bench. Thompson returned from injury to lead Golden State with 28 points, including six 3-pointers.<ref name=ap_06072019/>\n\nSiakam added 19 points for the Raptors.<ref name=ap_06072019/> VanVleet needed seven stitches in the fourth quarter after the Warriors' [[Shaun Livingston]] inadvertently elbowed him in the face.<ref name=stein_06072019/> The only other player to score over 10 points for Golden State, Curry had 27 points, but shot just 9 for 22 and missed 7 of his 9 three-point attempts. Looney returned to score 10 points after Kerr initially declared him out for the series following his Game 2 injury.<ref name=ap_06072019/><ref name=stein_06072019/>\n\n===Game 5===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 10 |time=9:00pm |place=[[Scotiabank Arena]], [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]] |TV=[[Sportsnet|SN]]/[[Citytv]], [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]], [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1='''[[Golden State Warriors]]''' |score1='''106'''\n|team2=[[Toronto Raptors]] |score2=105\n|report=[http://www.nba.com/games/20190610/GSWTOR#/boxscore Box score]\n|Q1='''34'''\u201328 |Q2=28\u201328 |Q3=22\u201322 |Q4=22\u2013'''27'''\n|points1=[[Stephen Curry]] 31 |points2=[[Kawhi Leonard]] 26\n|rebounds1=[[Draymond Green]] 10 |rebounds2=Kawhi Leonard 12\n|assist1=Draymond Green 8 |assist2=Leonard, [[Kyle Lowry|Lowry]] 6 each\n|attendance=20,144\n|referee=James Capers, Jason Phillips, Ed Malloy\n|series=Toronto leads series, 3\u20132\n}}\nCurry scored 31 points and Thompson had 26 to help the Warriors stave off elimination with a 106\u2013105 win at Toronto. They combined for three straight 3-pointers after the Raptors led by six points with {{frac|3|1|2}} minutes left in the game.<ref name=ap_06112019/> Durant returned after missing the previous nine games with his right calf injury,<ref name=ap_06112019/> and scored 11 points in the first quarter.<ref name=stein_06102019>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|title=How the Warriors Survived Game 5 of the N.B.A. Finals|date=June 10, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/sports/warriors-raptors.html|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref> However, he was lost for the game two minutes into the second quarter when he tried to drive by Ibaka and suffered a [[Achilles tendon rupture|ruptured Achilles tendon]], falling and grabbing his lower right calf. He limped off the court and was helped to the locker room.<ref name=stein_06102019/><ref name=letourneau_06122019/> Leonard scored 10 straight points in the fourth quarter to erase Golden State's 14-point lead.<ref name=ap_06112019/> Lowry's potential game-winning, 3-point shot at the buzzer fell short after it was partially blocked by Green.<ref name=ap_06112019>{{cite news|title=Warriors hang on to stay alive, win Game 5 of NBA Finals|date=June 11, 2019|website=ESPN.com|agency=Associated Press|url=https://global.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401134819|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=brady_06102019>{{cite news|last=Brady|first=Rachel|title=Raptors lose nail-biter Game 5 to Warriors, sending NBA Finals back to Oakland|date=June 10, 2019|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/article-raptors-lose-nail-biter-game-5-to-warriors-sending-finals-back-to/|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGolden State made 20 three-pointers, the second most in NBA Finals history behind Cleveland's 24 against the Warriors in Game 4 in [[2017 NBA Finals|2017]].<ref name=stein_06102019/> Cousins, who did not enter the game until Durant's injury, had 14 points and six rebounds for the Warriors, and Green added 10 points, 10 rebounds and eight assists.<ref name=stein_06102019/> Leonard had 26 points for the Raptors, while Lowry added 18 and Gasol 17 to lead six Raptors in double figures.<ref name=brady_06102019/> Golden State played most of the second half without Looney, who aggravated his cartliage fracture after colliding with Lowry while battling for a rebound.<ref name=stein_06102019/><ref>{{cite news|last=Letourneau|first=Connor|title=Warriors list Kevon Looney as questionable for Game 6 of NBA Finals|date=June 12, 2019|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/warriors/article/Warriors-list-Kevon-Looney-as-questionable-for-13976637.php|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDurant left the arena on crutches and in a [[walking boot]]. \"I don't believe there's anybody to blame [for Durant's injury], but I understand in this world, and if you have to, you can blame me,\" said [[Bob Myers]], the Warriors' president of basketball operations.<ref name=stein_06102019/> Durant underwent surgery to repair the tendon, and was at risk of potentially missing all of the following season.<ref name=letourneau_06122019>{{cite news |first=Connor|last=Letourneau|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/warriors/article/Warriors-Kevin-Durant-has-MRI-in-New-York-but-13973241.php | title=Warriors' Kevin Durant has surgery on torn Achilles; Kerr explains playing him | newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle  | date=June 12, 2019 | accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref> Originally expected to become a free agent after the 2018\u201319 season, he had a $31.5 million option to remain with Golden State for another season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Friedell|first=Nick|title=Sources: Warriors believe KD has torn Achilles|date=June 11, 2019|website=ESPN.com|url=https://global.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26944533/warriors-believe-kd-torn-achilles|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNurse was criticized for calling a timeout with Toronto up 103\u201397 after going on a 12\u20132 run; the Splash Brothers' three 3-pointers came after the break.<ref>{{cite news|last=Boren|first=Cindy|title=Raptors Coach Nick Nurse ripped for timeout that helped the Warriors|date=June 11, 2019|newspaper=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/06/11/raptors-coach-nick-nurse-ripped-timeout-that-helped-warriors/|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gantner|first=Mike|title=Raptors refuse to lose sight of what's important|date=June 13, 2019|website=Canada.com|publisher=Postmedia|url=https://beta.canada.com/sports/basketball/nba/toronto-raptors/raptors-refuse-to-lose-sight-of-whats-important/wcm/8afb65ca-01df-4ac0-90f6-e79e963c10b3/amp|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref> In its [[Last Two Minutes report]], the NBA stated that Cousins should have been called for a shooting foul on Gasol with 49 seconds left in the game, which would have given Gasol two free throws with the Raptors trailing 106\u2013103 at the time.<ref>{{cite news|title=NBA says Gasol should have gone to foul line late in Game 5|url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/06/11/nba-cousins-fouled-gasol-final-minute-game-5|website=NBA.com|date=June 11, 2019|access-date=June 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Carroll|first=Charlotte|title=NBA Says DeMarcus Cousins Fouled Marc Gasol in Final Minute of Game 5|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2019/06/11/demarcus-cousins-foul-marc-gasol-klay-thompson-nba-finals-game-5|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=June 11, 2019|access-date=June 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/basketball/nba/nba-concedes-referees-missed-a-potentially-game-changing-foul-on-raptors-marc-gasol | title=NBA concedes referees missed a potentially game-changing foul against Raptors\u2019 Marc Gasol | newspaper=National Post | date=June 12, 2019 | accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Game 6===\n{{Basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 13 |time=9:00pm {{small|(6:00 pm [[Pacific Time Zone|PDT]])}}|place=[[Oracle Arena]], [[Oakland, California]] |TV=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]/[[CTV Television Network|CTV]], [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]], [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1='''[[Toronto Raptors]]''' |score1='''114'''\n|team2=[[Golden State Warriors]] |score2=110\n|report=[http://www.nba.com/games/20190613/TORGSW#/boxscore Box score]\n|Q1='''33'''\u201332 |Q2='''27'''\u201325 |Q3=26\u2013'''31''' |Q4='''28'''\u201322\n|points1=[[Pascal Siakam|Siakam]], [[Kyle Lowry|Lowry]] 26 each|points2=[[Klay Thompson]] 30\n|rebounds1= Pascal Siakam 10 |rebounds2=[[Draymond Green]] 19\n|assist1=Kyle Lowry 10 |assist2=Draymond Green 13\n|attendance=19,596\n|referee=Marc Davis, David Guthrie, John Goble\n|series=Toronto wins series, 4\u20132\n}}\n\nLeonard scored 22 points and had six rebounds and was named the [[Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award|NBA Finals MVP]] after Toronto won 114\u2013110 over Golden State to claim its first championship in franchise history. Thompson scored a game-high 30 points for the Warriors, but was lost for the game with 2:22 remaining in the third quarter after landing awkwardly and suffering a [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|torn anterior cruciate ligament]] (ACL) in his left knee on a drive to the basket contested by Danny Green. The Warriors managed to remain in the game until a missed 3-pointer by Curry in the final seconds of the game. Trying to secure the ball after the miss, Golden State called a timeout, but they did not have any left, and were assessed a [[technical foul]]. It was academic, as time would have otherwise expired had they not attempted to stop the clock.<ref name=stein_06132019>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|title=How the Raptors Won Their First N.B.A. Championship|date=June 13, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/13/sports/warriors-raptors.html|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLowry and Siakam led Toronto with 26 points each. Lowry scored 11 of his points in the first two-plus minutes of the contest. Van Vleet finished with 22 points, including 12 in the final period, and made five of the team's 13 three-pointers. Siakam added 10 rebounds. Curry had 21 points for Golden State, but he was hounded by the Raptors in the fourth quarter without Durant or Thompson available. Draymond Green had a triple-double with 11 points, 19 rebounds and 13 assists, but committed eight turnovers. Iguodala had 22 points despite shooting only 1 of 5 on free throws.<ref name=stein_06132019/>\n\nLeonard averaged 28.5 points per game in the series,<ref>{{cite news|last=Windhorst|first=Brian|title=Kawhi 1st to win Finals MVP in both conferences|date=June 14, 2019|website=ESPN.com|url=https://global.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26969557/kawhi-1st-win-finals-mvp-conferences|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref> and joined [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] and [[LeBron James]] as the only players to be named Finals MVP with two different teams. Toronto was the first Canadian team to win the NBA title, and the first non-American team to win any of the [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|Big Four]] North American sports titles since the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] of [[Major League Baseball]] won the [[World Series]] in [[1993 World Series|1993]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rush |first1=Curtis |title=Toronto Raptors Are Kings Of The NBA And The Toast Of Canada |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/curtisrush/2019/06/14/toronto-raptors-are-kings-of-the-nba-and-the-toast-of-canada |website=Forbes |accessdate=June 14, 2019 |date=June 13, 2019}}</ref> This was the Warriors' last game ever at [[Oracle Arena]], as they moved to the new [[Chase Center]] in [[San Francisco]] at the beginning of the [[2019\u201320 NBA season|2019\u201320 season]]. They finished 0\u20133 at home in the series.<ref name=stein_06132019/>\n\n==Rosters==\n\n===Toronto Raptors===\n{{NBA roster header|team=Toronto Raptors|season=2018\u201319}}\n<!-- list of players -->\n{{player2 | num = 3 | first = OG | last = Anunoby | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 8 | lbs = 232 | college = Indiana | DOB = 1997\u201307\u201317 | }}\n{{player2 | num = 25 | first = Chris | last = Boucher | dab = basketball | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 10 | lbs = 200 | college = Oregon | DOB = 1993\u201301\u201311 }}\n{{player2 | num = 33 | first = Marc | last = Gasol | pos = C | ft = 7 | in = 1 | lbs = 255 | from = Spain | DOB = 1985\u201301\u201329 }}\n{{player2 | num = 14 | first = Danny | last = Green | dab = basketball | pos = G/F | ft = 6 | in = 6 | lbs = 215 | college = North Carolina | DOB = 1987\u201306\u201322 }}\n{{player2 | num = 9 | first = Serge | last = Ibaka | pos = FC | ft = 6 | in = 10 | lbs = 235 | from = Republic of the Congo | DOB = 1989\u201309\u201318 }}\n{{player2 | num = 2 | first = Kawhi | last = Leonard | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 7 | lbs = 230 | college = San Diego State | DOB = 1991\u201306\u201329 }}\n{{player2 | num = 17 | first = Jeremy | last = Lin | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 3 | lbs = 200 | college = Harvard | DOB = 1988\u201308\u201323 }}\n{{player2 | num = 7 | first = Kyle | last = Lowry | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 0 | lbs = 196 | college = Villanova | DOB = 1986\u201303\u201325 }}\n{{player2 | num = 8 | first = Jordan | last = Loyd | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 4 | lbs = 210 | college = Indianapolis | DOB = 1993\u201307\u201327 | note = TW }}\n{{player2 | num = 1 | first = Patrick | last = McCaw | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 7 | lbs = 185 | school = UNLV | DOB = 1995\u201310\u201325 }}\n{{player2 | num = 20 | first = Jodie | last = Meeks | pos = SG| ft = 6 | in = 4 | lbs = 210 | college = Kentucky | DOB = 1987\u201308\u201321}}\n{{player2 | num = 13 | first = Malcolm | last =