 the lack of legal availability of YouTube TV in Canada at the time of the 2019 NBA Finals, as it is tangential at best, despite the image in the next section depicting YouTube TV in the Scotiabank Arena-->\n\n==Media coverage==\n[[File:1 matt devlin jack armstrong 2019.jpg|thumb|Toronto Raptors commentary team members Matt Devlin and Jack Armstrong in the Scotiabank Arena during Game 2]]\nIn the United States, the Finals was televised by [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and [[ESPN Deportes]] in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. Play-by-play commentator [[Mike Breen]], and analysts [[Jeff Van Gundy]] and [[Mark Jackson]] called the series on ABC, while [[\u00c1lvaro Mart\u00edn (sports announcer)|\u00c1lvaro Mart\u00edn]] (play-by-play) and Carlos Morales (analyst) were on ESPN Deportes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lucia|first=Joe|title=Your 2019 NBA Finals announcing schedule|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/schedules/your-2019-nba-finals-announcing-schedule.html|website=AwfulAnnouncing.com|date=May 28, 2019|access-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, the Raptors' and the NBA's main local rightsholders, [[Sportsnet]] (which aired games 1, 3, and 5, and would have aired game 7) and [[The Sports Network|TSN]] (games 2, 4, and 6) aired separate, local telecasts with the Raptors' commentary team of [[Matt Devlin (sportscaster)|Matt Devlin]] on play-by-play, and [[Leo Rautins]] or [[Jack Armstrong (basketball)|Jack Armstrong]] as analysts. TSN sister broadcast television network [[CTV 2]] aired simulcasts of ABC's feed for games 2 and 4 in order to enforce [[simultaneous substitution]] rights on ABC stations carried on pay television,<ref>{{cite press release|title=TSN Announces Schedule for NBA Finals, Featuring Toronto Raptors vs. Golden State Warriors|url=https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/tsn-announces-schedule-for-nba-finals-featuring-toronto-raptors-vs-golden-state-warriors|publisher=Bell Media|language=en-US|date=May 27, 2019|access-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref> while game 6 was simulcast on [[CTV Television Network|CTV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://brioux.tv/blog/2019/06/12/ctv-jumps-on-raptors-bandwagon-for-thursdays-game-6/|first=Bill|last=Brioux|title=CTV jumps on Raptors\u2019 bandwagon for Game 6 Thursday|date=June 12, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref> Sportsnet's sister broadcast network [[Citytv]] similarly simulcast games 3 and 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/05/30/where-to-watch-raptors-nba-final/|title=Where to watch Raptors vs. Warriors NBA finals|website=CityNews Toronto|publisher=Rogers Media|access-date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]] broadcast all six games in [[French language|French]].\n\nAs the NBA's sole Canadian franchise, the Raptors' parent company [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]] (which is, in turn, majority owned between a partnership of Sportsnet and TSN's respective owners, [[Rogers Communications]] and [[BCE Inc.]]) manages the league's national media rights in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Zelkovich|url=http://thestar.blogs.com/sportsmedia/2010/06/sportsnet-back-in-the-game-with-raptors.html|title=Sportsnet back in the game with Raptors|work=Toronto Star|date=June 16, 2010|accessdate=July 14, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619061120/http://thestar.blogs.com/sportsmedia/2010/06/sportsnet-back-in-the-game-with-raptors.html|archivedate=June 19, 2010}}</ref> The series technically marked the first time that a team's regional broadcaster has produced its own coverage of games during the NBA Finals; these local broadcasts had access to ABC's camera feeds, along with additional cameras that were part of its own production resources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsvideo.org/2019/06/05/nba-finals-2019-as-raptors-fever-takes-over-canada-mlse-serves-up-game-coverage-on-sportsnet-tsn/|title=NBA Finals 2019: As Raptors Fever Takes Over Canada, MLSE Serves Up Game Coverage on Sportsnet, TSN|last=Dachman|first=Jason|website=Sports Video Group|language=en|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Viewership ===\n{{See also|NBA Finals television ratings}}\n\nIn Canada, Game 1 recorded an average of 3.3 million viewers on Sportsnet, making it the highest-rated NBA game in Canadian history.<ref name=ca_g1_ratings>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/sports/raptors-set-canadian-tv-record-in-game-1-of-nba-finals-but-u-s-ratings-down-1.4446921|title=Raptors set Canadian TV record in Game 1 of NBA Finals, but U.S. ratings down |website=CTV News|agency=Canadian Press|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref> By contrast, with 10.77 million U.S. viewers, Game 1 was the lowest-rated NBA Finals game in the U.S. since 2013, and the lowest-rated Game 1 in the Finals since 2009. Analysts cited both the presence of a Canadian team (Canadian viewership does not count towards U.S. Nielsen ratings, leading to only one U.S. home market being reflected in viewership), and being the first NBA Finals not to feature a team with [[LeBron James]] since 2010, as factors in the drop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-ratings-nba-finals-game-1-lowest-rating-in-10-years-1203230050/|title=NBA Finals Game 1 Scores Lowest Ratings in 10 Years|last=Thorne|first=Will|last2=Thorne|first2=Will|date=May 31, 2019|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/nba-finals-open-low-tv-ratings-thursday-may-30-2018-1214755|title=TV Ratings: NBA Finals Open With 10-Year Low|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref> In the Warriors' home market, ratings were also lower in comparison to its past Game 1 appearances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/nba/game-1-of-the-nba-finals-pulled-in-the-lowest-overnight-for-a-finals-game-since-2013-thanks-to-a-few-factors.html|title=Game 1 of the NBA Finals pulled in the lowest overnight for a Finals game since 2013, thanks to a few factors|date=May 31, 2019|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Canadian record would be surpassed by Game 2, with an average of 4.3 million across TSN, the French-language broadcast on RDS, and CTV2's simulcast of ABC's broadcast, and an estimate that the game was seen at any point by at least 10 million viewers. The game also had a 68% ratings share in the Toronto market. Game 3 was seen by 3.8 million viewers across Sportsnet and Citytv.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-ratings-nba-finals-game-3-2-1203234742/|title=TV Ratings: NBA Finals Game 3 Stays Low|last=Thorne|first=Will|date=June 6, 2019|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=ca_g23_ratings>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsvideo.org/2019/06/07/ratings-roundup-as-canadien-fans-carry-2019-nba-finals-the-tennis-channels-coverage-of-the-french-open-jumps-47-from-2018/|title=Ratings Roundup: As Canadian Fans Carry 2019 NBA Finals, the Tennis Channel\u2019s Coverage of the French Open Jumps 47% from 2018|last=Hernandez|first=Kristian|website=Sports Video Group|language=en|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref> The downward trend of U.S. viewership continued on Game 4, with a 9.8 share for the Friday-night game (a 12.5% year-over-year decline over Game 4 in 2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/friday-ratings-nba-finals-game-4-ratings-tumble-from-2018-1202629543/|title=Friday Ratings: NBA Finals Game 4 Ratings Take A Tumble From 2018 As Raptors Win Again|last=Haring|first=Bruce|last2=Patten|first2=Dominic|date=June 8, 2019|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=June 9, 2019|last3=Patten|first3=Dominic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2019/06/nba-finals-game-4-ratings-abc-overnights/|title=NBA Finals posts lowest Game 4 overnight since 2007|date=June 8, 2019|website=Sports Media Watch|language=en-US|access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref> TSN reported average viewership of 4.631 million, surpassing Canadian NBA viewership records for the third time in the series.<ref name=ca_g4_ratings>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/06/10/toronto-raptors-set-another-canadian-tv-record-for-game-4-of-nba-finals/|title=Toronto Raptors set another Canadian TV record for Game 4 of NBA Finals|website=CityNews Toronto|access-date=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nU.S. Game 5 viewership was 37% higher over Game 4, at 18.22 million, while Sportsnet reported an average of 6.4 million viewers across Sportsnet and the Citytv simulcast of ABC coverage\u2014surpassing the series finale of ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'' (4.33 million), [[Super Bowl LIII]] (4.34 million), and the [[91st Academy Awards]] (5.21 million)<ref>{{cite web |title=Top Programs \u2013 Total Canada (English) February 18, 2019 - February 24, 2019 |url=http://assets.numeris.ca/Downloads/February%2018,%202019%20-%20February%2024,%202019%20(National).pdf |publisher=[[Numeris]] |accessdate=March 13, 2019 |date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> as the [[List of most watched television broadcasts in Canada|most-watched television broadcast]] of 2019 in Canada, and once again the most-watched NBA telecast in Canada. The NBA itself estimated 6.9 million viewers when accounting for the French-language feed on RDS and estimated viewership on out-of-market stations.<ref name=bucholtz_06122019>{{Cite web|first=Andrew|last=Bucholtz|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/international/nba-finals-game-5-sees-raptors-set-another-canadian-record.html|title=NBA Finals Game 5 set another Canadian record, beat Big Bang Theory finale|date=June 12, 2019|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/warriors-comeback-nba-finals-ratings-2019-high-game-5-nba-abc-1202630796/|title=NBA Finals Ratings Hit 2019 High With Game 5 Warriors\u2019 Comeback; Down From 2017|last=Patten|first=Dominic|date=June 11, 2019|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGame 6 further exceeded these numbers with an average of 7.7 million. TSN publicized that a total of 15.9 million unique viewers watched some point of the telecast, and 9.99 million were watching during the final minute. TSN also reported that Game 6 had an 82% share of viewers in the [[Greater Toronto and Hamilton Area|Toronto\u2013Hamilton]] market\u2014which it stated to be the highest in the region for a sports broadcast outside of the [[Olympic Games]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/06/14/toronto-raptors-set-another-canadian-television-record-on-title-night/|title=Toronto Raptors set another Canadian television record on title night|website=CityNews Toronto|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> Game 6's ratings in the United States were slightly higher over Game 5, with 18.34 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/nba-finals-close-strong-tv-ratings-thursday-june-13-2019-1218363|title=TV Ratings: Strong Numbers for Toronto Raptors' NBA Title Clincher|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Game\n! scope=\"col\"|[[Nielsen ratings|Ratings]]<br />(American households)\n! scope=\"col\"|American audience<br />(in millions)\n! scope=\"col\"|Canadian average audience<br />(in millions)\n! scope=\"col\" class=unsortable|Ref\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|1\n| 7.9 || 13.31 || 3.3 || <ref>{{cite news|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Thursday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 5.30.19|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-thursday-cable-originals-network-finals-5-30-2019.html|website=ShowBuzzDaily.com|date=May 31, 2019|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=ca_g1_ratings/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|2\n| 8.0 || 13.88 || 4.3 || <ref>{{cite news|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 6.2.19|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-6-2-2019.html|website=ShowBuzzDaily.com|date=June 4, 2019|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=ca_g23_ratings/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|3\n| 7.8 || 13.10 || 3.8 || <ref>{{cite news|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 6.5.19|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-6-5-2019.html|website=ShowBuzzDaily.com|date=June 6, 2019|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=ca_g23_ratings/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|4\n| 4.3 || 12.79 ||  4.6 || <ref name=ca_g4_ratings/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Welch |first1=Alex |title=NBA Finals Game 4 adjusts up, \u2018NBA Countdown\u2019 and \u2018Jimmy Kimmel Live: Game Night\u2019 adjust down: Friday final ratings |url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/friday-final-ratings-june-7-2019/ |website=TV By The Numbers |accessdate=14 June 2019 |language=en |date=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|5\n| 6.5 || 18.22 || 6.4 || <ref name=bucholtz_06122019/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rejent |first1=Joseph |title=The NBA Finals adjust up: Monday final ratings |url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/monday-final-ratings-june-10-2019/ |website=TV By The Numbers |accessdate=14 June 2019 |language=en |date=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|6\n| 10.7 || 18.34 || 7.7 || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2019/06/nba-finals-game-6-ratings-raptors-warriors/|title=A blockbuster in Canada, Raptors\u2019 win draws healthy rating in U.S.|author=Paulson|publisher=Sports Media Watch|accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! Avg || 7.5 || 14.94 || 5.021\n|}\n\n==Victory parade==\n[[File:Toronto Raptors victory parade on We The North Day - 2019 (48086025892).jpg|thumb|263px|Toronto's [[Nathan Phillips Square]] on June 17, 2019 with crowds surrounding the [[3D Toronto sign]]]]\nOn June 17, the Raptors held a victory parade in downtown Toronto, which began at the [[Princes' Gates]] at the east end of [[Exhibition Place]], traveled<!--Use American English per article notes--> east along [[Lake Shore Boulevard|Lake Shore Boulevard West]], north along York Street and [[University Avenue (Toronto)|University Avenue]], east along [[Queen Street (Toronto)|Queen Street West]], and finished at [[Nathan Phillips Square]] next to [[Toronto City Hall]].<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-parade-route-1.5175920</ref> This parade was attended by an estimated crowd of two million fans, making this [[List of largest peaceful gatherings|the largest public gathering in one place for one event in Canadian history]], peacetime or wartime. However, due to this overcrowding, the parade was delayed an additional three hours as numerous fans bypassed the barricades, blocking the parade route.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-victory-parade-problems-1.5179508</ref> In addition, excessive crowds delayed emergency services from properly attending to various crowd participants falling ill and transporting them to nearby hospitals, which resulted in the death of an infant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/news/local-news/crowds-at-raptors-parade-played-role-in-infants-death|title=Crowdsat Raptors parade played role in infant's death? &#124; Toronto Sun|date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> Later on, the parade was marred by shootings, which occurred during the victory speeches.<ref name=torontoshooting /> The shootings wounded four people, though did not inflict life-threatening injuries, and caused a stampede.<ref name=torontoshooting>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/video/2019/jun/18/toronto-raptors-victory-parade-marred-by-shooting-and-stampede-video-report|title=Toronto Raptors' victory parade marred by shooting and stampede \u2013 video report|date=June 18, 2019|publisher=SNTV/Reuters|accessdate=June 19, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Three suspects were arrested and two guns were recovered.<ref name=torontoshooting />\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{official}}\n*[https://www.basketball-reference.com/playoffs/2019-nba-finals-warriors-vs-raptors.html 2019 NBA Finals] at Basketball-Reference.com\n*{{imdbtitle|10392366}}\n\n{{NBA Finals}}\n{{Toronto Raptors 2018\u201319 NBA champions}}\n{{Toronto Raptors}}\n{{Golden State Warriors}}\n{{2018\u201319 NBA season by team}}\n{{NBA on ABC}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Sports|San Francisco Bay Area|Canada|Ontario}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019 NBA Finals}}\n[[Category:2018\u201319 NBA season|Finals]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association Finals]]\n[[Category:May 2019 sports events in the United States|NBA Finals]]\n[[Category:June 2019 sports events in the United States|NBA Finals]]\n[[Category:May 2019 sports events in Canada|NBA Finals]]\n[[Category:June 2019 sports events in Canada|NBA Finals]]\n[[Category:Golden State Warriors games|NBA]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in California|NBA Finals]]\n[[Category:2010s in Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:2019 in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2010s in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Toronto]]\n[[Category:2018\u201319 in Canadian basketball]]\n[[Category:Toronto Raptors]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_NBA_Finals"}
{"title_page": "Jordan Chatman", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional basketball player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Jordan Chatman\n| image  =\n| caption = Chatman lays the ball up vs Virginia\n| number = 25\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 5\n| weight_lbs = 195\n| league        = [[Romanian Basketball Division A|Romanian League]]\n| team          = CSU Sibiu\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = American\n| high_school = \n*[[Union High School (Camas, Washington)|Union]]<br/>([[Camas, Washington]])\n| college = \n*[[Boston College Eagles men's basketball|Boston College]] (2016\u20132019)\n| draft_year = 2019\n| career_start = 2019\n| career_end = \n| years8        = 2019\u2013present\n| team8         = [[CSU Sibiu|Sibiu]]\n| highlights = \n*[[Washington Mr. Basketball]] (2012)\n}}\n\n'''Jordan Reid Chatman''' is an American professional basketball player, who currently plays in Romania for [[CSU Sibiu]]. Chatman played college basketball for [[Boston College]] and was a standout high school basketball player, being named [[Washington Mr. Basketball]] in 2012.\n\n==High school career==\nChatman grew up in [[Vancouver, Washington]] and attended [[Union High School (Camas, Washington)|Union High School]]. As a senior in 2011-12, he averaged 20.7 points, 6.3 rebounds, 2.7 assists, and 1.9 steals per game, leading the team to a 21-8 record and third place finish in the state tournament. He averaged 27 points per game during the tournament run earning tournament MVP honors. Chatman won the 2012 Washington Boys Basketball [[Washington Mr. Basketball|Gatorade Player of the Year award]].\n\n==College career==\nAs a sophomore at Boston College, he averaged 8.6 points per game, shooting 41.7 percent from behind the arc.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Geisinger |first1=Brian |title=Led by Jerome Robinson, Is Boston College the ACC's Most Dangerous Bubble Team? |url=https://accsports.com/acc-analytics/jerome-robinson-bc-acc-most-dangerous-bubble-team/ |website=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> His best game came on January 29, 2017 against the [[Virginia Tech Hokies men's basketball|Virginia Tech Hokies]], scoring 30 points and made nine consecutive threes pointers, which set an [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865672229/Watch-Former-BYU-guard-Jordan-Chatman-sets-new-ACC-record-for-most-consecutive-3-pointers-in-a-game.html|title=Watch: Former BYU guard Jordan Chatman sets new ACC record for most consecutive 3-pointers in a game|last=Yeomans|first=Jay|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> During his junior season, Chatman averaged 12.9 points, 2.9 rebounds, and 1.6 assists per game, hitting 87 three-pointers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baliatico |first1=Adam |title=Boston College Basketball Season Preview: The Guards |url=https://247sports.com/college/boston-college/Article/boston-college-basketball-season-preview-ky-bowman-jordan-chatman-wynston-tabbs-123961169/ |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=247 Sports |date=October 29, 2018}}</ref> On December 9, 2017, Chatman scored 22 points and helped the [[Boston College Eagles]] beat the previously undefeated and #1 nationally ranked [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2017/12/09/boston-college-upsets-no-1-duke-89-84/108462998/|title=Boston College rocks No. 1 Duke 89-84; Blue Devils' 1st loss|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> He scored 30 points in a 78-73 overtime win against [[Richmond Spiders men's basketball|Richmond]] on December 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Powtak |first1=Ken |title=Chatman\u2019s 30 carries BC past Richmond 78-73 in overtime |url=https://apnews.com/1fd6e3c9c63f426890750bfaea5e98ae |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=December 23, 2017}}</ref> During his senior season (2017-18), Chatman dealt with ankle and finger injuries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/02/12/bc-overcomes-more-injuries-to-pull-away-from-pitt/|title=Boston College overcomes more injuries to pull away from Pitt|work=[[Boston Herald]]|last=Hewitt|first=Steve|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://bcheights.com/2018/12/17/boston-college-mens-basketball-fairfield-notebook/|title=Notebook: Perimeter Defense Struggles, But BC Escapes|last=Smart|first=Bradley|work=The Heights|date=December 17, 2018|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> He averaged 13.2 points per game.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Golen |first1=Jimmy |title=Final Four or bust for Boston College. Wait ... What? |url=https://apnews.com/9ca8c4ad2c344cc69593b67acb1a8204 |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn July 2019, Chatman signed with [[CSU Sibiu]], a professional basketball team in Romania that competes in the [[Liga Na\u021bional\u0103 (men's basketball)|Liga Na\u021bional\u0103]]  and [[FIBA Europe Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosu |first1=Madalina |title=Jordan Chatman, de la Boston College, noul juc\u0103tor al CSU Sibiu |url=https://www.oradesibiu.ro/2019/07/25/jordan-chatman-de-la-boston-college-noul-jucator-al-csu-sibiu/ |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=Ora de Sibiu |date=July 25, 2019 |language=Romanian}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nChatman is the son of Jeff and Leah Chatman and is the second-oldest of eight children. Jeff Chatman played for the [[BYU Cougars]] from 1984-1988 and is seventh all time at [[BYU]] in scoring. Chatman served as a [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary]] for [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] for two years (2012\u20132014) in [[Taipei, Taiwan]] where he learned to speak fluent [[Mandarin Chinese]].<ref name=block>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/765566033/Jordan-Chatman-a-chip-off-the-ol-block.html|title=Former BYU star's son Jordan Chatman is a chip off the ol' block|work=[[Deseret News]]|last=Harmon|first=Dick|date=April 4, 2012|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> He graduated with a degree in China Studies.<ref name=drew>{{cite news |last1=Drew |first1=Jay |title=BYU basketball: Degree in hand, guard Jordan Chatman will transfer |url=https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=3989741&itype=CMSID |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=[[Salt Lake Tribune]] |date=June 9, 2016}}</ref> While at [[Boston College]], Chatman completed his [[Master of Business Administration]] degree.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900009459/three-reasons-why-former-byu-guard-jordan-chatman-is-loving-his-experience-at-boston-college.html|title=Three reasons why former BYU guard Jordan Chatman is loving his experience at Boston College|last=Toone|first=Trent|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=February 8, 2018|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Michael |title=Man Among the Boys: Jordan Chatman\u2019s Mission for Faith and Basketball |url=https://bcheights.com/2016/11/10/man-among-boys-jordan-chatman-mission-faith-basketball/ |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=The Heights |date=November 10, 2016}}</ref> His wife is a [[Taiwan]] native.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://bceagles.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/jordan-chatman/10420 Boston College Eagles bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chatman, Jordan}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Romania]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vancouver, Washington]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:BYU Cougars men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Boston College Eagles men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional basketball player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Jordan Chatman\n| image  =\n| caption = Chatman lays the ball up vs Virginia\n| number = 25\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 5\n| weight_lbs = 195\n| league        = [[Romanian Basketball Division A|Romanian League]]\n| team          = CSU Sibiu\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = American\n| high_school = \n*[[Union High School (Camas, Washington)|Union]]<br/>([[Camas, Washington]])\n| college = \n*[[Boston College Eagles men's basketball|Boston College]] (2016\u20132019)\n| draft_year = 2019\n| career_start = 2019\n| career_end = \n| years8        = 2019\u2013present\n| team8         = [[CSU Sibiu|Sibiu]]\n| highlights = \n*[[Washington Mr. Basketball]] (2012)\n}}\n\n'''Jordan Reid Chatman''' is an American professional basketball player, who currently plays in Romania for [[CSU Sibiu]]. Chatman played college basketball for [[Boston College]] and was a standout high school basketball player, being named [[Washington Mr. Basketball]] in 2012.\n\n==High school career==\nChatman grew up in [[Vancouver, Washington]] and attended [[Union High School (Camas, Washington)|Union High School]]. As a senior in 2011-12, he averaged 20.7 points, 6.3 rebounds, 2.7 assists, and 1.9 steals per game, leading the team to a 21-8 record and third place finish in the state tournament. He averaged 27 points per game during the tournament run earning tournament MVP honors. Chatman won the 2012 Washington Boys Basketball [[Washington Mr. Basketball|Gatorade Player of the Year award]].\n\n==College career==\nAs a sophomore at Boston College, he averaged 8.6 points per game, shooting 41.7 percent from behind the arc.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Geisinger |first1=Brian |title=Led by Jerome Robinson, Is Boston College the ACC's Most Dangerous Bubble Team? |url=https://accsports.com/acc-analytics/jerome-robinson-bc-acc-most-dangerous-bubble-team/ |website=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> His best game came on January 29, 2017 against the [[Virginia Tech Hokies men's basketball|Virginia Tech Hokies]], scoring 30 points and made nine consecutive threes pointers, which set an [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865672229/Watch-Former-BYU-guard-Jordan-Chatman-sets-new-ACC-record-for-most-consecutive-3-pointers-in-a-game.html|title=Watch: Former BYU guard Jordan Chatman sets new ACC record for most consecutive 3-pointers in a game|last=Yeomans|first=Jay|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> During his junior season, Chatman averaged 12.9 points, 2.9 rebounds, and 1.6 assists per game, hitting 87 three-pointers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baliatico |first1=Adam |title=Boston College Basketball Season Preview: The Guards |url=https://247sports.com/college/boston-college/Article/boston-college-basketball-season-preview-ky-bowman-jordan-chatman-wynston-tabbs-123961169/ |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=247 Sports |date=October 29, 2018}}</ref> On December 9, 2017, Chatman scored 22 points and helped the [[Boston College Eagles]] beat the previously undefeated and #1 nationally ranked [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2017/12/09/boston-college-upsets-no-1-duke-89-84/108462998/|title=Boston College rocks No. 1 Duke 89-84; Blue Devils' 1st loss|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> He scored 30 points in a 78-73 overtime win against [[Richmond Spiders men's basketball|Richmond]] on December 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Powtak |first1=Ken |title=Chatman\u2019s 30 carries BC past Richmond 78-73 in overtime |url=https://apnews.com/1fd6e3c9c63f426890750bfaea5e98ae |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=December 23, 2017}}</ref> During his senior season (2017-18), Chatman dealt with ankle and finger injuries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/02/12/bc-overcomes-more-injuries-to-pull-away-from-pitt/|title=Boston College overcomes more injuries to pull away from Pitt|work=[[Boston Herald]]|last=Hewitt|first=Steve|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://bcheights.com/2018/12/17/boston-college-mens-basketball-fairfield-notebook/|title=Notebook: Perimeter Defense Struggles, But BC Escapes|last=Smart|first=Bradley|work=The Heights|date=December 17, 2018|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> He averaged 13.2 points per game.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Golen |first1=Jimmy |title=Final Four or bust for Boston College. Wait ... What? |url=https://apnews.com/9ca8c4ad2c344cc69593b67acb1a8204 |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn July 2019, Chatman signed with [[CSU Sibiu]], a professional basketball team in Romania that competes in the [[Liga Na\u021bional\u0103 (men's basketball)|Liga Na\u021bional\u0103]]  and [[FIBA Europe Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosu |first1=Madalina |title=Jordan Chatman, de la Boston College, noul juc\u0103tor al CSU Sibiu |url=https://www.oradesibiu.ro/2019/07/25/jordan-chatman-de-la-boston-college-noul-jucator-al-csu-sibiu/ |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=Ora de Sibiu |date=July 25, 2019 |language=Romanian}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nChatman is the son of Jeff and Leah Chatman and is the second-oldest of eight children. Jeff Chatman played for the [[BYU Cougars]] from 1984-1988 and is seventh all time at [[BYU]] in scoring. Chatman served as a [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary]] for [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] for two years (2012\u20132014) in [[Taipei, Taiwan]] where he learned to speak fluent [[Mandarin Chinese]].<ref name=block>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/765566033/Jordan-Chatman-a-chip-off-the-ol-block.html|title=Former BYU star's son Jordan Chatman is a chip off the ol' block|work=[[Deseret News]]|last=Harmon|first=Dick|date=April 4, 2012|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> He graduated from BYU with a degree in China Studies.<ref name=drew>{{cite news |last1=Drew |first1=Jay |title=BYU basketball: Degree in hand, guard Jordan Chatman will transfer |url=https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=3989741&itype=CMSID |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=[[Salt Lake Tribune]] |date=June 9, 2016}}</ref> While at [[Boston College]], Chatman completed his [[Master of Business Administration]] degree.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900009459/three-reasons-why-former-byu-guard-jordan-chatman-is-loving-his-experience-at-boston-college.html|title=Three reasons why former BYU guard Jordan Chatman is loving his experience at Boston College|last=Toone|first=Trent|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=February 8, 2018|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Michael |title=Man Among the Boys: Jordan Chatman\u2019s Mission for Faith and Basketball |url=https://bcheights.com/2016/11/10/man-among-boys-jordan-chatman-mission-faith-basketball/ |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |work=The Heights |date=November 10, 2016}}</ref> His wife is a [[Taiwan]] native.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://bceagles.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/jordan-chatman/10420 Boston College Eagles bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chatman, Jordan}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Romania]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vancouver, Washington]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:BYU Cougars men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Boston College Eagles men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Shooting gua